  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "The clinical presentation of pulmonary embolism can vary widely, but dyspnea, pleuritic chest pain, and tachycardia are common findings. Risk factors include recent immobilization or surgery, malignancy, pregnancy, oral contraceptive use, and hereditary thrombophilia. The most common source of pulmonary emboli is deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in the lower extremities. The electrocardiogram may show sinus tachycardia, right axis deviation, right bundle branch block, or the classic S1Q3T3 pattern (prominent S wave in lead I, Q wave in lead III, and inverted T wave in lead III), but these findings are neither sensitive nor specific. D-dimer levels are often elevated in patients with pulmonary embolism, but a normal D-dimer level in a patient with low clinical probability can help exclude the diagnosis. Definitive diagnosis requires imaging studies such as CT pulmonary angiography or ventilation-perfusion scanning."
