  "source": {
    "file_name": "European Respiratory Society Guidelines for Bronchiectasis",
    "content": "Management of bronchiectasis includes antibiotic therapy targeted at colonizing pathogens, airway clearance techniques, and bronchodilators. For Pseudomonas aeruginosa infections, which are associated with more severe disease and worse outcomes, fluoroquinolones (e.g., ciprofloxacin) are recommended as first-line oral therapy. Long-term macrolide therapy may be considered in patients with frequent exacerbations. Bronchodilators and mucoactive agents can improve symptoms and quality of life by enhancing mucus clearance. Surgical intervention is reserved for localized disease with persistent symptoms despite optimal medical management, or for recurrent severe hemoptysis not controlled by bronchial artery embolization."
