  "source": {
    "file_name": "Critical Care Medicine",
    "content": "The immediate management of massive hemoptysis (>200-500 mL/24 hours) should prioritize airway protection, oxygenation, and hemodynamic stabilization. Endotracheal intubation with a double-lumen tube is often necessary to isolate and protect the non-bleeding lung, prevent asphyxiation, and facilitate bronchoscopy. The bleeding side should be positioned dependent to prevent blood spillage into the non-bleeding lung. Blood transfusion, correction of coagulopathies, and fluid resuscitation are essential for hemodynamic stabilization. Once the patient is stabilized, bronchial artery embolization is the preferred intervention for controlling the bleeding, with success rates of 80-90%. Surgical resection may be considered in cases of recurrent massive hemoptysis, localized disease (such as aspergilloma), or when embolization fails. Aspergilloma, a fungal ball formed by Aspergillus species colonizing a pre-existing pulmonary cavity (often post-tuberculosis), is a common cause of massive hemoptysis due to erosion of bronchial arteries by the fungal ball, and typically appears as a mobile intracavitary mass with an air crescent on imaging."
  },
