  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "The approach to a patient with nephrotic syndrome typically includes a 24-hour urine collection for protein. While dipstick measurements of protein excretion roughly correlate with 24-hour measurements (1+ corresponds approximately to 30 mg/dL, 2+ to 100 mg/dL, 3+ to 300 mg/dL, and 4+ to 1000 mg/dL or greater), the precision of the measurement is greatly enhanced by a timed collection. The presence of oval fat bodies indicates lipiduria associated with nephrotic syndrome. A 24-hour urine protein excretion >3.5 g is consistent with nephrotic-range proteinuria in adults."
