  "source": {
    "file_name": "Journal of the American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons - Intertrochanteric Hip Fractures",
    "content": "Intramedullary nailing has become the preferred treatment for unstable intertrochanteric fractures (AO/OTA 31-A2 and A3), particularly those with posteromedial comminution or reverse obliquity patterns. Biomechanical studies demonstrate that intramedullary devices provide superior stability for unstable fracture patterns compared to sliding hip screws, with reduced moment arm and improved load sharing properties. Clinical studies consistently show lower rates of fixation failure, malunion, and reoperation with intramedullary nails in unstable fracture patterns. Additional advantages include shorter operative time, reduced blood loss, and the potential for earlier weight-bearing. These factors are particularly important in elderly patients with comorbidities who benefit from early mobilization to prevent complications of prolonged recumbency. While sliding hip screws remain a viable option for stable fracture patterns (31-A1), the growing body of evidence supports the superiority of intramedullary fixation for unstable patterns, especially in osteoporotic bone. Arthroplasty is rarely indicated as primary treatment for intertrochanteric fractures, being reserved primarily for salvage of failed fixation or in select cases of severe osteoarthritis with concurrent hip fracture."
  },
