  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "Bacterial (septic) arthritis is a medical emergency that can lead to rapid joint destruction and irreversible loss of function. The most common causative organisms in adults include Staphylococcus aureus, streptococci, and gram-negative bacilli. Routes of infection include hematogenous spread, direct inoculation through trauma or medical procedures, and contiguous spread from adjacent infections. Clinical presentation typically includes acute onset of monoarticular joint pain, swelling, warmth, erythema, and restricted motion, often accompanied by fever and chills. Laboratory findings include leukocytosis, elevated ESR and CRP, and synovial fluid analysis showing turbid or purulent fluid with >50,000 WBC/mm³ (predominantly neutrophils), low glucose, and positive Gram stain or culture. Prompt diagnosis and treatment with joint drainage and appropriate antibiotics are essential to prevent joint destruction."
