  "source": {
    "file_name": "KELLEY & FIRESTEIN'S TEXTBOOK OF RHEUMATOLOGY",
    "content": "Serologic abnormalities are a hallmark of SLE. Antinuclear antibodies (ANAs) are found in virtually all patients, but are not specific for SLE. Anti-double-stranded DNA (anti-dsDNA) antibodies are highly specific for SLE, occurring in 60% to 70% of patients, and their titers often correlate with disease activity, particularly renal involvement. Anti-Smith (anti-Sm) antibodies are also highly specific for SLE but less sensitive, present in only 20% to 30% of patients. Hypocomplementemia, particularly decreased levels of C3 and C4, is common during active disease and reflects complement consumption by immune complexes. This finding is especially prevalent in patients with active nephritis. The presence of anti-dsDNA antibodies together with hypocomplementemia is highly suggestive of active SLE, particularly when renal involvement is present."
