  "source": {
    "file_name": "The New England Journal of Medicine",
    "content": "Vitamin B12 deficiency can lead to hematologic, neurologic, and gastrointestinal manifestations. Neurologic symptoms include paresthesias, peripheral neuropathy (particularly affecting position and vibration sense), dementia, delirium, and subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord. Psychiatric manifestations can range from irritability and depression to severe dementia or frank psychosis. Importantly, neurologic symptoms may occur without hematologic abnormalities and can be irreversible if treatment is delayed. Vitamin B12 deficiency may be particularly common in older adults due to atrophic gastritis, decreased intrinsic factor production, and use of medications like metformin and proton pump inhibitors that can interfere with B12 absorption. Diagnosis is typically made by measuring serum B12 levels, though methylmalonic acid and homocysteine levels may be more sensitive markers, particularly in cases with borderline B12 levels. Treatment with parenteral B12 supplementation can result in rapid improvement of hematologic abnormalities, while neurologic improvement may be slower and sometimes incomplete if treatment is delayed."
