  "source": {
    "file_name": "The Lancet Neurology",
    "content": "Management of behavioral variant frontotemporal dementia (bvFTD) is primarily symptomatic, as no disease-modifying treatments have been proven effective. Acetylcholinesterase inhibitors (e.g., donepezil) and memantine have not shown efficacy in FTD and may worsen behavioral symptoms in some cases. For behavioral symptoms, which can be distressing and disruptive, environmental modifications and behavioral management strategies are first-line approaches. When pharmacological intervention is necessary, atypical antipsychotics at low doses may help manage severe behavioral disturbances, disinhibition, and agitation, though they should be used cautiously due to increased mortality risk in elderly patients with dementia. Risperidone and quetiapine are commonly used, starting at the lowest possible dose and titrating carefully. SSRIs such as sertraline may help with compulsive behaviors, depression, and anxiety. Trazodone has shown some benefit for agitation and sleep disturbances. Non-pharmacological approaches include maintaining routines, simplifying the environment, providing clear communication, offering limited choices, and redirecting inappropriate behaviors."
  },
