  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "Lung cancer should be suspected in any patient with a new or changing cough, particularly in individuals with significant smoking history. The presence of hemoptysis, weight loss, or a mass on imaging studies further increases the likelihood of malignancy. Common symptoms include cough, hemoptysis, dyspnea, chest pain, and systemic symptoms such as weight loss and fatigue. CT findings suggestive of lung cancer include a spiculated or irregular mass, nodules, mediastinal lymphadenopathy, and pleural effusion. The definitive diagnosis requires tissue confirmation through bronchoscopy, CT-guided biopsy, or surgical procedures."
