  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 20th Edition",
    "content": "The management of diabetic ketoacidosis consists of (1) fluid replacement, (2) insulin administration, (3) electrolyte repletion, and (4) identification and treatment of the precipitating cause. Initial fluid therapy should aim to replace the estimated water deficit (typically 4-6 L in an average-sized adult) over the first 24 hours. In patients who are not in shock, normal saline (0.9% NaCl) at a rate of 15-20 mL/kg in the first hour, followed by 4-14 mL/kg/hr, is appropriate. Regular insulin should be administered as a continuous intravenous infusion at an initial rate of 0.1 units/kg/hr after an optional initial IV bolus of 0.1 units/kg. Blood glucose should be monitored hourly, and the insulin infusion rate should be adjusted to achieve a decline in blood glucose by 50-70 mg/dL/hr. Potassium, phosphate, and bicarbonate deficits should be replaced as necessary."
