    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "The diagnosis of diabetes is established by identifying elevated levels of plasma glucose in the fasting state (fasting plasma glucose ≥126 mg/dL or ≥7.0 mmol/L) or after a glucose challenge (2-h value in the oral glucose tolerance test ≥200 mg/dL or ≥11.1 mmol/L). A hemoglobin A1C (HbA1C) ≥6.5% is also used to diagnose diabetes. The presence of classical symptoms of diabetes such as polyuria, polydipsia, and weight loss, plus a random plasma glucose concentration ≥200 mg/dL is also diagnostic of diabetes."
