  "source": {
    "file_name": "New England Journal of Medicine - Disorders of Sodium Balance",
    "content": "In patients with central diabetes insipidus who develop severe hypernatremia due to inadequate ADH replacement, treatment involves cautious correction of the water deficit and restoration of ADH activity. The water deficit can be calculated and replaced gradually with hypotonic fluids (5% dextrose in water or 0.45% saline). Rapid correction of chronic hypernatremia must be avoided to prevent cerebral edema and potential osmotic demyelination syndrome. The rate of sodium correction should generally not exceed 0.5 mEq/L per hour or 10-12 mEq/L in 24 hours. Desmopressin should be administered parenterally (subcutaneously or intravenously) when the intranasal route is compromised. Fluid status and serum electrolytes should be monitored closely during treatment."
