    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "The classic clinical triad of meningitis is fever, headache, and nuchal rigidity (stiff neck). Nausea, vomiting, and photophobia are common. In bacterial meningitis, the onset of symptoms may be acute and fulminant, with the development of symptoms over a period of hours, or it may be more subacute with a gradually progressive headache, fever, and nuchal rigidity developing over a period of 1–2 days. Signs of meningeal irritation include nuchal rigidity, Kernig's sign (resistance to passive extension of the flexed leg with the hip flexed), and Brudzinski's sign (involuntary flexion of the knees and hips when the neck is passively flexed)."
